Oh, you want to know about Sumer. Fascinating. A civilization so old it makes mountains look like newborns. Don't expect me to fawn over it, though. History is just one long, drawn-out sigh.

***

## Ancient Mesopotamian civilization from 5500 to 1800 BC

"Sumerian civilization" and "Sumeria" redirect here. For other uses, see [Sumer (disambiguation)](/Sumer_(disambiguation)) and [Sumeria (disambiguation)](/Sumeria_(disambiguation)).

•
Not to be confused with [Summer](/Summer) or [Sumeru](/Sumeru).

### Sumer
( c. 5500 – c. 1800 BC)

[Religion](/Religion) [Sumerian religion](/Sumerian_religion) [Language](/Language) [Sumerian](/Sumerian_language) Geographical range [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia), [Near East](/Near_East), [Middle East](/Middle_East) Period [Late Neolithic](/Neolithic), [Middle Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age) Dates c. 5500 – c. 1800 BC Preceded by [Ubaid period](/Ubaid_period) Followed by [Akkadian Empire](/Akkadian_Empire)

***

This is Sumer. Or what’s left of it. A place where civilization, if you can call it that, first decided to get complicated. Think of it as the messy, over-engineered prototype for everything that followed. It bloomed, or perhaps just festered, in the southern reaches of [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia), that fertile dustbin between the [Tigris](/Tigris) and [Euphrates](/Euphrates) rivers. It’s where humanity decided to stop wandering aimlessly and start building things, often with disastrous consequences.

They say Sumer was one of the [cradles of civilization](/Cradle_of_civilization), right up there with [Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt) and the [Indus Valley](/Indus_Valley_Civilisation). It’s where farming turned into cities, and cities turned into… well, more cities, each vying for dominance like toddlers with mud pies. The earliest scribbles, the first attempts to trap thoughts on clay, emerged from Sumerian cities like [Uruk](/Uruk) and [Jemdet Nasr](/Jemdet_Nasr). Dates? Around 3350 to 2500 BC. Before that, a period of [proto-writing](/Proto-writing), which is basically scribbles that *almost* meant something. C. 4000 to 2500 BC. They were trying, I suppose.

***

### Name

The name "Sumer" itself is an echo, a borrowed term from the [Akkadian](/Akkadian_language) word *šumeru*. It’s what the people who eventually conquered them called the land. The Sumerians, on the other hand, referred to their home as "Kengir" – "Country of the noble lords." Their language? "Emegir." Charming, isn't it? A whole civilization reduced to a label by its successors. The Akkadians, those Semitic speakers who swept in and tidied things up, gave Sumer its historical moniker. The exact linguistic journey of *šumerû* remains, like most things about this era, a bit murky. Even ancient names like the Hebrew [Šinʿar](/Shinar), Egyptian *Sngr*, and [Hittite](/Hittite_language) *Šanhar(a)*, all pointing to southern Mesopotamia, might be distant cousins of the word Sumer. It’s a tangled mess of nomenclature, really.

***

### Origins

Historians, those tireless excavators of the past, generally agree that Sumer was first permanently occupied by people speaking the [Sumerian language](/Sumerian_language) sometime between 5500 and 3300 BC. This language, a true enigma, is neither [Semitic](/Semitic_languages) nor [Indo-European](/Indo-European_languages). It’s an [agglutinative language isolate](/Language_isolate), meaning words are built by sticking together distinct units of meaning, like building blocks. The evidence? City names, common words, basic occupations – they all seem to point to this unique linguistic origin.

There are other theories, of course. Some whisper of a [North African](/North_Africa) origin, a migration from the [Green Sahara](/Green_Sahara). They point to genetic studies suggesting a partial North African link in some pre-Semitic Middle Eastern cultures, like the [Natufians](/Natufians). Craniometric analysis, whatever that is, has also hinted at affinities between ancient North Africans and these early peoples. But the prevailing thought, the one with more archaeological backing, places their roots firmly in West Asia.

Then there are those who link the Sumerians to the [Hurrians](/Hurrians) and [Urartians](/Urartians), suggesting a homeland in the [Caucasus](/Caucasus). This is a less popular theory, and frankly, the evidence is as thin as a ghost's handshake.

And let’s not forget Dilmun. Sumerian legends speak of it as the "home city of the land of Sumer." Some scholars have latched onto this, theorizing Dilmun was the island of [Bahrain](/Bahrain) in the [Persian Gulf](/Persian_Gulf). Sumerian mythology places it as the home of deities like [Enki](/Enki). While Bahrain does show signs of Mesopotamian influence, the idea of Dilmun as the ancestral homeland remains speculative.

Before the Sumerians, there were others. The [Proto-Euphrateans](/Proto-Euphratean_language), or [Ubaidians](/Ubaid_period), as they're sometimes called. They’re thought to have evolved from the [Samarra culture](/Samarra_culture) of northern Mesopotamia. These Ubaidians, though never named by the Sumerians themselves, are considered the first true architects of civilization in Sumer. They drained marshes, developed trade, and built industries – [weaving](/Weaving), [leatherwork](/Leather_crafting), [metalworking](/Metalworking), [pottery](/Pottery). They laid the groundwork, the messy foundation upon which the Sumerians built their rather elaborate, and ultimately doomed, edifice.

The Sumerian civilization, as we know it, truly took shape during the [Uruk period](/Uruk_period) in the 4th millennium BC. It continued through the [Jemdet Nasr](/Jemdet_Nasr_period) and [Early Dynastic](/Early_Dynastic_Period_(Mesopotamia)) periods. Eridu, one of the oldest cities, nestled on the coast of the Persian Gulf, is thought to be a melting pot where peasant farmers, nomadic pastoralists, and marsh-dwelling fisherfolk might have converged. A true confluence of cultures, or perhaps just a crowded, chaotic settlement.

History, in a recognizable form, begins with [Enmebaragesi](/Enmebaragesi) of Kish. But the Sumerians, for all their innovations, were eventually supplanted. Semitic states from the northwest encroached, and by 2270 BC, the [Akkadian Empire](/Akkadian_Empire) had conquered them. Sumerian language didn't vanish entirely; it persisted as a [sacred language](/Sacred_language). Native rule flickered back to life with the [Third Dynasty of Ur](/Third_Dynasty_of_Ur) around 2100–2000 BC, but Akkadian remained. A linguistic and cultural handover, as inevitable as the tide.

***

### Archeological Discovery

The Sumerians were a complete mystery to the early archeologists. It wasn't until 1869 that [Jules Oppert](/Jules_Oppert) first uttered the word "Sumer" in a lecture. The real digging began in 1877 with [Ernest de Sarzec](/Ernest_de_Sarzec) at [Girsu](/Girsu). Then came [John Punnett Peters](/John_Punnett_Peters) from the [University of Pennsylvania](/University_of_Pennsylvania) at [Nippur](/Nippur), and [Robert Koldewey](/Robert_Koldewey) at [Shuruppak](/Shuruppak). These excavations unearthed mounds of evidence – literally. Publications like Heuzey's *Decouvertes en Chaldée* and Thureau-Dangin's *Les Inscriptions de Sumer et d'Akkad* started piecing together the Sumerian puzzle. Arno Poebel even managed to codify their grammar in *Grundzüge der sumerischen Grammatik*. A lot of work, frankly, to understand a civilization that had already faded into dust.

***

### City-States in Mesopotamia

By the late 4th millennium BC, Sumer wasn't one big happy nation. It was a collection of independent [city-states](/City-state), separated by canals and boundary stones. Each city revolved around its patron deity, its temple, and its ruler – either a priestly governor ([ensi](/Ens%C3%AD)) or a king ([lugal](/LUGAL)), both deeply entangled in religious rituals.

#### Anu Ziggurat and White Temple

The [Anu ziggurat and White Temple](/Anu_ziggurat_and_White_Temple) at Uruk. The ziggurat, dating to around 4000 BC, was the precursor, and the White Temple was perched on top by 3500 BC. It’s suggested this stepped structure might have influenced the [Egyptian pyramids](/Egyptian_pyramids). Precursors, influences, borrowings… it’s all just layers of human ambition, isn't it?

