### History

Sumerian city-states rose and fell, a cycle as predictable as the sunrise. Their written history starts around the 27th century BC, but it’s murky until the Early Dynastic III period, around the 23rd century BC, when the writing becomes clearer.

The [Akkadian Empire](/Akkadian_Empire), a Semitic state, was the first to try and hold this whole region together. It didn't last. After a brief [Gutian period](/Gutian_period), the [Ur III kingdom](/Third_Dynasty_of_Ur) tried again, uniting parts of Mesopotamia. But [Amorite](/Amorites) incursions at the dawn of the second millennium BC put an end to that. The Amorite "dynasty of [Isin](/Isin)" clung on until about 1700 BC, when [Babylonia](/Babylonia) finally unified the region.

